# transon — project overview

Homogeneous JSON-to-JSON template engine: `Transformer(template).transform(data)`.
Full engine specification: `docs/SPECIFICATION.md` — read it before non-trivial changes.

## Map

- `transon/transformers.py` — engine core (`Transformer`, `Context`, `NoContent`, errors)
- `transon/rules.py` — all built-in rules (`@Transformer.register_rule`)
- `transon/operators.py` / `transon/functions.py` — `expr` operators / `call` functions
- `transon/docs.py` — generates docs JSON from docstrings + test corpus
- `transon/tests/` — table-driven example cases that ARE the documentation examples
- `tests/` — plain pytest tests for engine mechanics and error paths

## Invariants (do not break)

- Templates are pure JSON; a dict containing the marker key (default `"$"`) is a rule
  invocation, everything else is copied literally. No string-embedded DSLs.
- Rule parameters are templates themselves — evaluate dynamic params with `t.walk()`.
- `t.NO_CONTENT` is the "no value" sentinel: produced by `attr`/`get` misses, skipped
  by `map`/`object`/`file`/`filter`. Preserve these skipping semantics.
- `DefinitionError` = malformed template; `TransformationError` = incompatible data.
- Registries (`_rules`, `_operators`, `_functions`) are MRO-resolved; subclassing
  `Transformer` resets them, so subclass registrations never affect the base class.
- `transform()` must never mutate the input data or the template.
- Code must stay compatible with Python 3.9+ (CI matrix 3.9–3.13). Stdlib only —
  no new runtime dependencies.

## Known quirks

Open and resolved engine-semantics issues (`NO_CONTENT` leaks, etc.) are
catalogued in `docs/ROADMAP.md` (items `R-01`…`R-22`, with fix options and decision
status). Never change behavior silently — resolved items need an explicit decision
recorded there and a changelog entry when templates may have relied on old behavior.
